(1) Acr. interpreted ‘iure’ by ‘exemplo, pacto, modo, potestate) If this could be, the sentence would run ‘ for all [i. e. all combatants] are awk- ward to deal with [ἀρ’γάλεοι, χαλεποί εἶσι] by that right [i. e. in virtue of that quality] by which brave men are so who meet in single combat.' Heindorf thought to amend this, but hardly does so, by taking the clause ‘ quihus adversum bellum incidit' as qualify- ing ‘omnes.’ It seems clear that ‘bel- lum,’ both here and in V. 16, has its proper sense of actual combat, and is opposed to civil quarrels.
